(12, 'Cheap Business class airline tickets, first class flights, business air flights', 'Cheap business class, first class, cheap flights, first class airline, cheap air ', 'FlyFirst Announces Top 10 U.S. Most Luxurious Airport Lounges', 'Cheap-First-Class-Flight', '2013-06-10 20:06:05', 'Escape at the Airport: Top 10 U.S. Lounges to Make Your Time on the Ground Worthwhile.&#160;The trend towards bigger, fancier and more&#160;luxurious airport lounges&#160;is a great boon to travelers. We&#39;ve compiled a list of our favorite U.S. airport lounges that are sure to make you want to hang out in the airport just a little bit longer than usual.\n', '<p>Escape at the Airport: Top 10 U.S. Lounges to Make Your Time on the Ground Worthwhile</p>\n\n    <p>The trend towards bigger, fancier and more&#160;<a href="http://www.flyfirst.com/" target="_blank" title="cheap business class Flights">luxurious airport lounges</a>&#160;is a great boon to travelers. We&#39;ve compiled a list of our favorite U.S. airport lounges that are sure to make you want to hang out in the airport just a little bit longer than usual</p>\n\n    <p>Virgin Atlantic Clubhouse, New York&#39;s JFK Airport&#160;<br />\n    Trendy and cosmopolitan, the JFK Clubhouse is 10,000 square feet of pure delight. Mingle in the modern bar, relax with a free 15-minute massage at Bumble &amp; Bumble salon or play a game of billiards. The Clubhouse is located in Terminal 4 and is open to Virgin Atlantic&#39;s Upper Class passengers, UK Amex Centurion card members and Virgin&#39;s Flying Club gold members.</p>\n\n    <p>Alaska Airlines Board Room, at Seattle-Tacoma Airport&#160;<br />\n    With a serene, contemporary ambiance, the Board Room is a satisfying retreat in Seatac&#39;s Concourse C. Savor complimentary Starbucks espresso, or sip on sodas, beer, wine or cocktails. Fresh snacks are offered throughout the day. Monthly special events feature local restaurants, brewers and winemakers. The Board Room, the 2012 Priority Pass Lounge of the Year, is open to Board Room members and MVP or Gold Alaska Airlines Mileage club members.</p>\n\n    <p><a href="http://www.flyfirst.com/" target="_blank" title="last minute business class">Oneworld Lounge</a>, Los Angles International&#160;<br />\n    Shared by British Airways, Japan Airways, Qantas and other Oneworld partners, the Oneworld Lounge sparkles with Macintosh computer terminals, a full bar, buffet, power outlets and comfortable seating. Located on the International Terminal&#39;s Level 5, the lounge is open to Oneworld airlines&#39; first and business class passengers and Oneworld Emerald and Sapphire members.</p>\n\n    <p>Virgin Atlantic at Liberty Airport in New Jersey&#160;<br />\n    Spacious and welcoming, the Clubhouse invites members to dine from an extensive menu, watch a movie on a large flat-screen television or rest in private sleeping pods. The 5,000 square foot clubhouse offers every workplace amenity, from charging stations and work surfaces to adapters. Located in Terminal B, the lounge is open to Upper Class passengers, Virgin&#39;s Flying Club gold members and UK Amex Centurion card members.</p>\n\n    <p>Cathay Pacific Lounge, San Francisco International&#160;<br />\n    White Italian marble, black Chinese granite and Venetian glass make this lounge an elegant oasis. Abundant fully-equipped workstations make it convenient to catch up on the office, and the trademark noodle bar offers delicious refreshment. Located on Level 4 of the International Terminal, the lounge is open to Cathay Pacific and Oneworld airlines&#39; first and business class passengers and Emerald and Sapphire Oneworld members.</p>\n\n    <p>American Airlines Admirals Club, Denver&#160;<br />\n    Woodsy and warm, the Admirals Club offers a cyber cafe featuring equipped workstations, a quiet zone, flat-screen televisions, a full-service bar and plentiful snacks and beverages. Located in Terminal A, the lounge is available to American Airlines&#39; business and first class passengers, Amex Platinum members and Oneworld Emerald and Sapphire members.</p>\n\n    <p>Delta SkyClub, Miami&#160;<br />\n    A little South Beach flair makes this lounge a fun, relaxing area. Shower suites, a chic bar, supple armchairs and a quiet zone lure travelers to the lounge. Located on Level 4, the SkyClub is open to Delta business class passengers, Delta Platinum or Reserve card members or a Diamond Medallion member,</p>\n\n    <p>Lufthansa Lounge, Boston&#39;s Logan Airport&#160;<br />\n    Lufthansa brings modern Bavarian treats to its passengers, with plentiful German brews, soft leather chairs and workstations. Remodeled in 2011, the lounge is located in Terminal E and open to Lufthansa&#39;s business, Senator and first class passengers.</p>\n\n    <p>Emirates Lounge, New York&#39;s JFK&#160;<br />\n    In true first-class tradition, the Emirates lounge offers an endless buffet, supple leather seating, shower suites and plentiful entertainment. Open to Emirates&#160;<a href="http://flyfirst.com/airline/Emirates" target="_blank" title="emirates">first and business clas</a>s passengers, the lounge is located at Terminal 4.</p>\n\n    <p><a href="http://flyfirst.com/airline/British-Airways" target="_blank" title="british airways">British Airways</a>&#160;Terraces Lounge, Seattle Tacoma&#160;<br />\n    Colorful seating, abundant workstations and bountiful drinks and snack make this lounge a winsome respite from the bustling airport. Available to British Airways first and business class travelers, BA Executive club members and Sapphire and Emerald Oneworld members, the lounge is located in the South Satellite terminal.</p>\n', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(14, 'cheap first class tickets business class last minute business deals', 'cheap business class first class deals last minute business class airfare first class tickets', 'Cheap Business and First Class this Summer, Save Thousands ', 'Business-Class-Cheap', '2013-06-17 16:35:29', 'With more than 1.5 billion Americans taking to the skies for vacations in 2012, the popular summer tourist season can get very busy. FlyFirst, a leading luxury travel booking service, advises travelers for business and pleasure to schedule their summer trips now, before the peak of the season is underway.&#160;\n', '<p>With more than 1.5 billion Americans taking to the skies for vacations in 2012, the popular summer tourist season can get very busy. FlyFirst, a leading luxury travel booking service, advises travelers for business and pleasure to schedule their summer trips now, before the peak of the season is underway. To help consumers save on summer travel,&#160;<a href="http://www.flyfirst.com/" target="_blank" title="Cheap Business Class Flights">FlyFirst offers</a>&#160;its four top tips for making the most of a travel budget during the peak season.</p>\n\n    <p>Research the destination. Tens of millions of U.S. travelers use the Internet to research their travel accommodations each year. Prospective travelers should put the power of the Internet to use in researching the destination and getting a feel for which summer months are the least expensive. Travel to and from China, for example, is rapidly increasing, and demand for seats on those flights is growing as well. In August, though, travel to China drops off, making it the perfect time to book a trip to the country.</p>\n\n    <p>Book in advance. Many airlines use on-demand pricing, so as the available seats are reserved, the pricing increases. This increase can be avoided if travelers book their flights in advance, when there are as many seats open as possible. In addition, other airline costs, such as oil and labor, may increase as the summer progresses, so booking early may help travelers avoid those cost increases.</p>\n\n    <p>If booking well in advance isn&#39;t possible, take advantage of unsold seats in other travel classes.<a href="http://flyfirst.com/continent/asia" target="_blank" title="cheap business class flight">Business class seats</a>&#160;rarely sell out, and those open seats can be purchased at discounted Y-Up fares. So, for those who need to find a flight within the next 30 days, calling the airline or an airline booking service and asking for available Y-Up fares in business class may be the way to go.</p>\n\n    <p>&quot;Only the very savvy travelers know to ask for the Y-Up discounts,&quot; notes Julia Graft, PR manager for FlyFirst. &quot;The discounts can be considerable, and vacationers can benefit from the extra space and amenities offered by business class in the process.&quot;</p>\n\n    <p>For some countries, business travel slows down in the summer. Many European countries, for instance, virtually shut businesses during the holiday month of August. For those destinations, check the pricing of business class tickets and first class fares. Since there is often unused capacity in those classes of travel, the prices may often be more affordable than one would expect. Prices for business class flights from Los Angeles to London, for example, decrease significantly in August.</p>\n\n    <p>Take advantage of frequent flier miles, credit card miles and services that can optimize those rewards. Countless credit card companies offer travel mileage accrual on everyday purchases and offer greater flexibility on redeeming airlines. Capital One Venture Rewards Card and Chase Sapphire Preferred Card both get high marks for flexibility and reward bonuses. To maximize the accrued reward points, travelers should consider using services that know all the ins and outs of the reward systems. Award travel booking services like&#160;<a href="http://www.awardgenius.com/" target="_blank" title="save money">AwardGenius.com</a>&#160;help consumers get the most out of their accrued points.</p>\n\n    <p>With a little planning, travelers can save considerably on travel during the bustling summer season. For information about saving money on summer travel and to find out more about the services provided by FlyFirst, call (888) 347-7817, or visit FlyFirst.com.</p>\n', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
